WE ARE, constant in our convictions and motivations, thirty years later we still possess a desire to do the right thing, to intervene and to do what we know in our hearts, is right. <br><br>
But, another thing I see is that, Vietnam was not the cause nor did it create the unrest of the sixties. It may have accelerated and politically reformed the anti-government movement but it did not give it birth. Many of the youth of that generation were spiritually starved and deprived of strong moral convictions and remain so today, hence, the warp social compromising we are subjected to today. <br><br>
There is also nothing wrong with our righteous indignation.  I believe the Vietnam veteran far more then others examines himself and the motive for his actions and response, more thoroughly before rendering judgment on the injustice we see daily. Yet, we still give in more often then not. Unknowingly, we express in silent love a compassion toward those who do wrong, by our willingness to believe or trust them, even at the expense of our own sufferings and shame.<br><br>
I donÆt believe there is anything wrong with righteous anger. It is the natural expression of who we are inwardly. We are the product of our times, traditions, moral upbringing and convictions.<br><br>
Our anger is justified in manifesting itself against the willful, high-handed, deliberate, inexcusable transgressions and the amorality we see occurring daily all around us. <br><br>
Art, it is a righteous indignation, compatible with our nature and morals, are you (except for little PP and MTF), more likely to step out of the shower to pee? But are we not at the same time, or just as often when we are hurt, when we are subjected to unnecessary suffering, are we not just as willing to allow the anger within us to manifest itself and do we not delight at times in allowing it to  run out of control? We feel an urge within to appease the gods of destruction, that the war never allowed us to satisfy? WasnÆt it there, we were able to react to a personified evil, an evil that was also trying to kill us. We see through shaded glasses, we are the victims of our own convictions. <br><br>
Perhaps that is why, I never took it personally, until one of my buddies got hurt (injustice), and when I responded and hurt them (killed and wounded the enemy, with m-60), they reacted. They reacted to the pain and suffering I had inflicted upon them and then they also made it personal. It was then that I began to realized that they were trying to kill me. <br><br>
In my eyes they were the aggressors against the weak and poor, we the knight in shinning armor. But I also realized that their rational for military involvement  could not be justified by their actions. Seeing this, gave rise to further my resolve and determination to reek havoc upon those who I had seen do so much wrong to others.  Perhaps it was at those times that to me it was my very own private world, and private war and that is why today, IÆm still proud for what I accomplished on the battlefield in Southeast Asia and why I, like you continue to strive to accomplish what we can to render justice to others through our local involvement in todayÆs political trenches and in what we can see we can do something about.<br><br>
